+4.145 KVM_SET_APF_EVENTFD
+-------------------------
+
+:Capability: KVM_CAP_ASYNC_PF_USERFAULT_EVENTFD
+:Architectures: x86
+:Type: vcpu ioctl
+:Parameters: struct kvm_apf_eventfd (in)
+:Returns: 0 on success, < 0 on error
+
+Errors:
+
+  ========== ===============================================================
+  EINVAL     Non-zero ``flags``, ``padding`` or ``reserved`` fields, ``fd``
+             is less than -1, ``fd`` equals ``complete_fd``, or both file
+             descriptors refer to the same eventfd context.
+  EBADF      Invalid file descriptor.
+  EBUSY      Async page faults are pending on the vCPU.
+  EFAULT     The parameter address was invalid.
+  ENOMEM     Kernel could not allocate the shared page.
+  ========== ===============================================================
+
+::
+
+  struct kvm_apf_eventfd {
+	__s32 fd;
+	__s32 complete_fd;
+	__u32 flags;
+	__u32 padding;
+	__u64 reserved[2];
+  };
+
+Registers eventfds for exitless async page fault notification. When
+registered, userfault async page faults write fault details to a shared
+ring buffer instead of exiting to userspace via ``KVM_EXIT_MEMORY_FAULT``.
+KVM signals ``fd`` only when userspace has armed notification via the
+shared page header. This avoids the KVM_RUN exit/re-entry overhead for
+each async page fault.
+
+The shared ring is allocated by the kernel for each successful
+registration. Userspace maps it via
+``mmap(vcpu_fd, PAGE_SIZE, PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_SHARED, offset =
+KVM_APF_PAGE_OFFSET * PAGE_SIZE)`` after the ioctl returns. This matches
+the mmap pattern used for ``KVM_DIRTY_LOG_PAGE_OFFSET`` /
+``KVM_COALESCED_MMIO_PAGE_OFFSET`` and avoids ``FOLL_LONGTERM``-pinning
+a userspace anon page. Userspace must mmap the shared ring again after
+replacing a registration. The layout is ``struct kvm_apf_shared_page``::
+
+  #define KVM_APF_SHARED_VERSION          1
+  #define KVM_APF_RING_SIZE               64
+  #define KVM_APF_SHARED_FLAG_NOTIFY_ARMED  _BITUL(0)
+
+  struct kvm_apf_shared_header {
+	__u32 version;
+	__u32 ring_size;
+	__u32 entry_size;
+	__u32 flags;
+	__u64 reserved[6];
+  };
+
+  struct kvm_apf_ring_entry {
+	__u64 gpa;
+	__u64 flags;
+  };
+
+  struct kvm_apf_ring {
+	__u32 head;
+	__u32 _pad_head[15];	/* cacheline isolation */
+	__u32 tail;
+	__u32 _pad_tail[15];
+	struct kvm_apf_ring_entry entries[KVM_APF_RING_SIZE];
+  };
+
+  struct kvm_apf_shared_page {
+	struct kvm_apf_shared_header header;
+	struct kvm_apf_ring notify;
+	struct kvm_apf_ring complete;
+  };
+
+The ``header`` identifies the shared page ABI and exposes the active ring
+shape. KVM initializes ``version`` to ``KVM_APF_SHARED_VERSION``,
+``ring_size`` to ``KVM_APF_RING_SIZE`` and ``entry_size`` to
+``sizeof(struct kvm_apf_ring_entry)``.  The ``reserved`` fields must be
+zero.
+
+The ring ``head`` and ``tail`` indices are placed on separate cachelines
+to avoid producer/consumer false sharing, so userspace MUST lay out the
+ring exactly as shown above.
+
+``head`` and ``tail`` are **free-running** ``__u32`` counters: the
+producer stores ``head + 1`` (unmasked), the consumer stores ``tail + 1``
+(unmasked), and both sides mask by ``KVM_APF_RING_SIZE - 1`` only when
+indexing into ``entries[]``. ``KVM_APF_RING_SIZE`` is a power of two, so
+modular arithmetic on ``__u32`` matches the masked index.
+
+The shared page contains two ring buffers:
+
+**Notification ring** (``notify``): KVM writes ``head``, userspace writes
+``tail``. When a userfault async page fault occurs, KVM writes the faulting
+GPA and flags to ``entries[head & (KVM_APF_RING_SIZE - 1)]`` and advances
+``head``. KVM signals ``fd`` only if
+``KVM_APF_SHARED_FLAG_NOTIFY_ARMED`` was set in ``header.flags``; KVM
+clears the flag before signaling. If the ring is full (``head - tail >=
+KVM_APF_RING_SIZE``), KVM falls back to a normal ``KVM_EXIT_MEMORY_FAULT``
+exit.
+
+Userspace should treat ``fd`` as a coalesced wakeup hint and the ring as
+authoritative. To wait without losing wakeups, userspace must drain the
+notification ring, atomically set ``KVM_APF_SHARED_FLAG_NOTIFY_ARMED`` in
+``header.flags``, execute a full memory barrier, re-read ``notify.head``
+with acquire semantics, and sleep on ``fd`` only if the ring is still empty.
+If the ring became non-empty after arming, userspace should clear
+``KVM_APF_SHARED_FLAG_NOTIFY_ARMED`` and process the entry instead of
+sleeping.
+
+**Completion ring** (``complete``): Userspace writes ``head``, KVM writes
+``tail``. When userspace has resolved a page fault, it writes the GPA to
+``entries[head & (KVM_APF_RING_SIZE - 1)]``, advances ``head``, and
+signals ``complete_fd``. KVM drains the ring and completes the
+corresponding async page faults. Completion entries must have a page-aligned
+``gpa`` and zero ``flags``; KVM ignores invalid completion entries. If
+userspace advances ``head`` more than ``KVM_APF_RING_SIZE`` entries ahead of
+``tail``, KVM treats the completion ring contents as ambiguous and drops the
+corrupt batch by advancing ``tail`` to ``head``.
+
+Both rings use ``smp_store_release`` / ``smp_load_acquire`` for the
+producer/consumer indices.
+
+Set ``fd`` to -1 to deregister. ``complete_fd`` is ignored when
+deregistering. Registration and deregistration fail with ``-EBUSY`` if
+async page faults are pending on the vCPU. After deregistration or
+replacement, old shared page mappings remain valid until userspace
+munmaps them, but the kernel no longer writes to them.
+
+Userfault async page faults delivered through the notification ring are
+implicitly accepted (equivalent to ``KVM_APF_OP_ACCEPT``). Userspace must
+resolve pages asynchronously and signal completion via the completion ring.
+If the notification ring is full and KVM falls back to
+``KVM_EXIT_MEMORY_FAULT``, the base ``KVM_ASYNC_PF`` rules apply.
+
+``flags``, ``padding`` and ``reserved`` must be zero. ``flags`` is
+currently unused and reserved for future extension; forwards-compatible
+userspace MUST pass 0 until kernel support is checked via
+``KVM_CHECK_EXTENSION``.
+
+
